[[Image:Barabus Kazan.jpg|thumb|350px|Barabuses in Kazan]] '''Barabus''' (rendering of [[Tatar language|Tatar]] ''barabız'' “we are going” + [[English language|English]] ''[[bus]]'') was a winter [[public transport]] in 19th – early 20th centuries, probably the first public transport in [[Kazan]] after [[taxicab|cab]]s. They were operated by private carriers who were poor [[Tatar]] [[commoner]]s from surrounding [[village]]s. A typical barabus was a [[sledge]] sheeted with [[Burlap|sacking]]. Barabus was a [[transport]] of [[pauper]]s competing with cabs, [[Horsecar|horse railways]] and later [[tram]]way. Until the 1930s, when trams were installed in the [[suburbs]] and any private enterprise was prohibited, barabuses were the only transport to connect quarters of poor mill-hands with other parts of the city.
