{{Nanoelec}} [[File:Nanowire laser.png|thumb|Nanowire lasers for ultrafast transmission of information in light pulses]] [[Semiconductor]] nanowire lasers are nano-scaled [[lasers]] that can be embedded on chips and constitute an advance for computing and information processing applications. Nanowire lasers are coherent light sources (single mode optical waveguides) as any other laser device, with the advantage of operating at the nanoscale. Built by [[molecular beam epitaxy]], nanowire lasers offer the possibility for direct integration on silicon, and the construction of optical interconnects and data communication at the chip scale. Nanowire lasers are built from III–V semiconductor heterostructures. Their unique 1D configuration and high refractive index allow for low optical loss and recirculation in the active nanowire core region. This enables subwavelength laser sizes of only a few hundred nanometers <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ning|first=C. Z.|date=2012|title=Semiconductor Nanowire Lasers|url=https://asu.pure.elsevier.com/en/publications/semiconductor-nanowire-lasers|journal=Semiconductors and Semimetals|language=en|volume=86|doi=10.1016/B978-0-12-391066-0.00012-5|issn=0080-8784}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nature.com/articles/nphoton.2009.184 Yan, Ruoxue, Daniel Gargas, and Peidong Yang. "Nanowire photonics." Nature photonics 3.10 (2009): 569-576]</ref>. Nanowires are Fabry–Perot resonator cavities defined by the end facets of the wire, therefore they do not require polishing or cleaving for high-reflectivity facets as in conventional lasers <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ning|first=C. Z.|date=2012|title=Semiconductor Nanowire Lasers|url=https://asu.pure.elsevier.com/en/publications/semiconductor-nanowire-lasers|journal=Semiconductors and Semimetals|language=en|volume=86|doi=10.1016/B978-0-12-391066-0.00012-5|issn=0080-8784}}</ref>.
==Properties== Nanowire lasers can be grown site-selectively on Si/SOI wafers with conventional [[molecular beam epitaxy|MBE]] techniques, allowing for pristine structural quality without defects. Nanowire lasers using the group-III nitride and ZnO materials systems have been demonstrated to emit in the visible and ultraviolet, however infrared at the 1.3–1.55 μm is important for telecommunication bands<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koblmüller|first=Gregor|last2=Mayer|first2=Benedikt|last3=Stettner|first3=Thomas|last4=Abstreiter|first4=Gerhard|last5=Finley|first5=Jonathan J.|date=2017|title=GaAs–AlGaAs core–shell nanowire lasers on silicon: invited review|url=http://stacks.iop.org/0268-1242/32/i=5/a=053001|journal=Semiconductor Science and Technology|language=en|volume=32|issue=5|pages=053001|doi=10.1088/1361-6641/aa5e45|issn=0268-1242|bibcode=2017SeScT..32e3001K}}</ref>. Lasing at those wavelengths has been achieved by removing the nanowire from the silicon substrate <ref>[https://www.nature.com/articles/nphoton.2009.184 Yan, Ruoxue, Daniel Gargas, and Peidong Yang. "Nanowire photonics." Nature photonics 3.10 (2009): 569-576]</ref>. Nanowire lasers have shown pulse durations down to <1ps <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sidiropoulos|first=Themistoklis P. H.|last2=Röder|first2=Robert|last3=Geburt|first3=Sebastian|last4=Hess|first4=Ortwin|last5=Maier|first5=Stefan A.|last6=Ronning|first6=Carsten|last7=Oulton|first7=Rupert F.|date=2014-09-28|title=Ultrafast plasmonic nanowire lasers near the surface plasmon frequency|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nphys3103|journal=Nature Physics|language=en|volume=10|issue=11|pages=nphys3103|doi=10.1038/nphys3103|bibcode=2014NatPh..10..870S}}</ref>, and enable repetition rates greater than 200GHz <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mayer|first=B.|last2=Janker|first2=L.|last3=Loitsch|first3=B.|last4=Treu|first4=J.|last5=Kostenbader|first5=T.|last6=Lichtmannecker|first6=S.|last7=Reichert|first7=T.|last8=Morkötter|first8=S.|last9=Kaniber|first9=M.|date=2016-01-13|title=Monolithically Integrated High-β Nanowire Lasers on Silicon|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.nanolett.5b03404|journal=Nano Letters|volume=16|issue=1|pages=152–156|doi=10.1021/acs.nanolett.5b03404|issn=1530-6984|bibcode=2016NanoL..16..152M}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mayer|first=B.|last2=Regler|first2=A.|last3=Sterzl|first3=S.|last4=Stettner|first4=T.|last5=Koblmüller|first5=G.|last6=Kaniber|first6=M.|last7=Lingnau|first7=B.|last8=Lüdge|first8=K.|last9=Finley|first9=J. J.|date=2017-05-23|title=Long-term mutual phase locking of picosecond pulse pairs generated by a semiconductor nanowire laser|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms15521|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=8|pages=ncomms15521|doi=10.1038/ncomms15521|arxiv=1603.02169|bibcode=2017NatCo...815521M}}</ref>. Also, nanowire lasers have shown to store the phase information of a pulse over 30ps when excited with subsequent pulse pairs. Mode locked lasers at the nano-scale are therefore feasible with such configurations.
